CRIMETIME: Using historical data to predict NYC crime rates.¶

Introduction¶

This is a blog post about the project I completed at Insight Data Science. The goal of the project was to develop a predictive model for crime rates in Manhattan using historical data provided by the NYC Open Data Website. This lead me to create a web application, CrimeTime, where users can preform similar analysis in their neighborhood anywhere in New York City.

In this blog we will be covering a few topics that involve learning from data and developing strategies for combating crime from the data. Specifically we will,

  • Perform exploratory analysis on geospatial and temporal crime data to find where and when specific crimes happen the most.

We will see that different crimes affect different areas in the Manhattan and that monthly crime rates peak at different points of the year depending on the type of crime. We then,

  • Develop a time series model that uses historical data to predict monthly number of crimes in two neighborhoods that have the highest crime rates in Manhattan.

Now that we can predict future montly crime rates in these neighborhoods we can allocate police resources to the neigborhoods at the appropriate time. Finally we look into,

  • Performing exploratory data analysis to help us uncover ways to reduce assaults in East Harlem.

First we start off mentioning a few libraries that were important:

We'll need the the geopy to figure out distances between points later

In [21]:
from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim

Now we can start to look into the the crime data!

Exploratory analysis on geospatial and temporal crime data¶

I cleaned the data beforehand put it into a sqlite database. The amount of data I used doesn't really make sense to use a SQL database, but while developing the code I found it was just easier to clean the data once than reading it in and cleaning it each time. So, I cleaned it and stored it in a SQLite database; this became paricularly useful when I looked into expanding the project to a web application. We can access the data very easily using sqlite3 database library and read it into a pandas dataframe:

In [24]:
import sqlite3
import pandas as pd
conn = sqlite3.connect('Manhattan.db')
crime_df = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM Crime_Data', conn)
conn.close()

You'll notice I only have data that from 2006 to 2015. The data for 2016 was not available at the time and the data before 2006 is rather sparse. Since the data before 2006 isn't so good and because it might not actually be better for forecasting I decided to neglect it. Let's get a look how crime in Manhattan has evolved over the last 9 years. We plot the number of crimes per year using matplotlib:

Let's focus in on the communities that were most effected by these two types of crime. Assaults in 2015 were highest in East Harlem, encompassing Police precints 23, 25 and 32, while larceny was highest in midtown encompassing Police precints 13, 14 and 18. We can now see that the over all trend is that Larceny rates in Midtown are declining, while assault rates in East Harlem are increasing. Since the two are out of phase with one another (occur at different times of the year), it may be possible to redirect police efforts to the different areas depending on the time of year. Let's develop a predictive model to use estimate the number of monthly crimes involving grand larceny in Midtown and the number of assaults in East Harlem using the time series data. Being able to predict the number of incidents on a month to month basis would be useful for police as they might be able to better prepare for increases and decreases in crime within the city and reallocate resources to specific neighborhoods at the appropriate time of year.

TIME SERIES ANALYSIS¶

There are lot of great resource for time series analysis. For this project I used some blogs:

A tutorial on time series model is a good place to start, but its in R, so I turned to, Tim series forecasting in python. Another good resource is Tom Augspurger's blog Finally for seasonal ARIMA I found the the following blog post really helpful.

I won't go over the details of modeling with ARIMA, but more information can be found in the links above. It's worth noting that R has a lot better time series capabilities than Python. However, one can use the statsmodels library to use ARIMA modeling.

ARIMA: Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average¶

ARIMA is a standard techinque for modeling and forecasting in time series analysis. The general model we are using is given by,

\begin{equation} C_{T} = \mu + \sum_{i=1}^{p} \gamma_{i} C_{T-i} +\sum_{i=0}^{q} \theta_{i} \epsilon_{T-i}. \end{equation}

Where $C_{T}$ is related to the number of crimes that occured in month $T$ and $\epsilon_{T}$ is a normally distributed random error. We can see that ARIMA incorporates trying to balance a linear combination of previous months number of crimes as well as a linear combination of this month's and previous months' random errors. An ARIMA model, ARIMA($p,d,q$), has three paramaters, $p,d,$ and $q$. $p$ and $q$ correspond to the maximum number of lags in the above equation, however the number $d$ corresponds to the number of differences in monlthy number of crimes before our data is stationary.

Seasonal ARIMA¶

Seasonal ARIMA is a little more complicated, it takes into effect the seasonality of the data and tries to fit an appropriate model labeled SARIMA$(P,D,Q)_{m}$ where $m$ is the seasonality, which in our case will turn out to be 12 since it is yearly. The Seasonal ARIMA model will therefore have 7 paramaters: $(p,d,q)$ for the non-seasonal ARIMA model an $(P,D,Q)_{m}$ for the seasonal version of ARIMA.

We preform some preliminary analysis on the Larceny data using the Dicky-Fuller test. This involves looking at differences and testing to see if the differences transform the data to being stationary.

We can see that the first difference and the first seasonal difference makes the data stationary, so we take $d=1$ and $D=1$. We can figure out the other values for creating the ACF AND PCF plots for the first difference:

In [62]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(211)
fig = sm.graphics.tsa.plot_acf(larceny_MT.first_difference.iloc[13:], lags=40,
                               ax=ax1)
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(212)
fig = sm.graphics.tsa.plot_pacf(larceny_MT.first_difference.iloc[13:], lags=40,
                                ax=ax2)

From this we see to choose $p=1$ and $q=2$. We can find the values for $P$ and $Q$ by making the ACF and PCF plots for the seasonal first differences:

In [63]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(211)
fig = sm.graphics.tsa.plot_acf(larceny_MT.seasonal_first_difference.iloc[13:],
                               lags=40, ax=ax1)
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(212)
fig = sm.graphics.tsa.plot_pacf(larceny_MT.seasonal_first_difference.iloc[13:],
                                lags=40, ax=ax2)

We can then see that we should choose $P=1$ and $Q=1$ for our model. We use these parameters in our models and fit the data. We can then print out the results of our model fitting.

In [64]:
mod_larceny = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(larceny_MT.Crimes, trend='n',
                                        order=(1,1,2), 
                                        seasonal_order=(1,0,1,12))
results_larceny = mod_larceny.fit()

print results_larceny.summary()

We can then inspect the performance of our model visually by comparing the number of monthly crimes over the last year to the number of recorded crimes:

In [65]:

date_list = [start + relativedelta(months=x) for x in range(0,12)]

larceny_MT_errors = pd.DataFrame(index=date_list, columns =['Recorded Crimes', 
                                                            'Predicted Crimes'])

temp = larceny_MT['Crimes']
larceny_MT_errors['Recorded Crimes'] = temp[105:117].values
larceny_MT_errors['Predicted Crimes'] = results_larceny.predict(start = 105,

Now we can figure out the distance between each assault and the closest subway:

In [146]:
NUM_STATIONS = east_harlem_stations.shape[0]
SUBWAY_LONGITUDE = east_harlem_stations['LONGITUDE'].as_matrix()
SUBWAY_LATITUDE = east_harlem_stations['LATITUDE'].as_matrix()
DISTANCES = np.ndarray(NUM_STATIONS)

CRIME_LATITUDE = assault_df['LATITUDE'].as_matrix()
CRIME_LONGITUDE = assault_df['LONGITUDE'].as_matrix()

NUM_CRIMES = len(CRIME_LATITUDE)
DISTANCES_TO_STATION = np.ndarray(NUM_CRIMES)

for i in range(0,NUM_CRIMES):
    crime_loc = (CRIME_LATITUDE[i], CRIME_LONGITUDE[i])
    for j in range(0,NUM_STATIONS):
        DISTANCES[j] = great_circle(crime_loc,
                              (SUBWAY_LATITUDE[j],SUBWAY_LONGITUDE[j])).miles
    DISTANCES_TO_STATION[i] = np.amin(DISTANCES)

assault_df['DISTANCE_TO_STATION'] = DISTANCES_TO_STATION

ASSAULTS_NEAR_STATION = assault_df[assault_df.DISTANCE_TO_STATION <= 0.25] 

print 'Assaults in East Harlem that occured within 1/4 mile of subway station '\
        + str(float(ASSAULTS_NEAR_STATION.shape[0])/float(assault_df.shape[0]))

Assaults in East Harlem that occured within 1/4 mile of subway station 0.521088769004

That's a large number of assaults that occur near a subway station! We could definitely improve public safety by increasing surveillance near public transportation stations! Conclusion¶

In this blog post we have looked into using exploratory data analysis to come up with data driven strategies to reduce crime in Manhattan. We used time series analysis to model monthly crime rates in both Midtown and East Harlem and validated the models. While there are definitely more interesting topics we could look into, but they will be saved for another blog post!
